Chapter 7: Self‑Diagnostics and Meta‑Recursion

7.1 Recursive Self‑Modeling with Martingale Monitors

The self‑model \mathcal{M}_{\text{self}} is itself a contracting system with a known ISS gain. The divergence \delta_k = \|s_k - \hat{s}_k\| forms a supermartingale under normal operation. The system can detect anomalies by checking whether \delta_k violates the Azuma–Hoeffding bounds.

Theorem 7.1 (Self‑Model Anomaly Detection)
If both the main system and the self‑model are ISS and the coupling between them is sufficiently weak such that the combined system satisfies the small‑gain condition with a known gain margin, then the divergence process satisfies the supermartingale property, and the probability of false anomaly detection can be made arbitrarily small by choosing appropriate thresholds.

Proof. The divergence can be expressed as a supermartingale difference sequence. The Azuma–Hoeffding inequality provides exponential bounds. The condition “sufficiently weak” is quantified by the small‑gain condition: the gain from the main system to the self‑model and back must satisfy \gamma_{\text{main}} \circ \gamma_{\text{model}}(s) < s. Under this condition, the combined system is ISS, and the divergence is bounded. The full proof is in Appendix A.12. ∎

7.2 Structural Plasticity

When a cognitive agent learns a new fault pattern, it modifies its internal representation. Any such modification must be validated against the SOS‑computed contraction metric. The software enforces that learning updates are performed only after a sufficient number of samples are collected, and the updated parameters are checked to ensure the Lipschitz constant remains below 1 and that the new metric is still positive definite over the region. This is done via incremental SOS verification or by using a bounded‑update rule (e.g., a projection onto the set of parameters that satisfy the contraction LMI).

