A.1 Proof of Theorem 2.1 (Incremental Exponential Convergence with ISS)

Theorem 2.1. Let \Phi : \mathcal{S} \times \mathcal{D} \to \mathcal{S} be a discrete‑time map and assume there exists a Riemannian metric g with distance d such that for all s,s'\in\mathcal{S} and disturbances d,d'

d\bigl(\Phi(s,d),\,\Phi(s',d')\bigr) \le \alpha \, d(s,s') + \gamma(\|d-d'\|),

with \alpha\in(0,1) and \gamma\in\mathcal{K}. Then for any two trajectories s_k, s'_k with \|d_k-d'_k\|\le \bar{d} we have

d(s_k,s'_k) \le \alpha^k d(s_0,s'_0) + \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha}.

Proof. We proceed by induction on k.

Base case k=0: The inequality d(s_0,s'_0)\le d(s_0,s'_0) is trivially true.

Inductive step: Assume the bound holds at step k. Then

\begin{aligned}
d(s_{k+1},s'_{k+1}) &\le \alpha \, d(s_k,s'_k) + \gamma(\|d_k-d'_k\|) \\
&\le \alpha \Bigl(\alpha^k d(s_0,s'_0) + \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha}\Bigr) + \gamma(2\bar{d}) \\
&= \alpha^{k+1} d(s_0,s'_0) + \alpha\frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha} + \gamma(2\bar{d}) \\
&= \alpha^{k+1} d(s_0,s'_0) + \gamma(2\bar{d})\Bigl(\frac{\alpha}{1-\alpha}+1\Bigr) \\
&= \alpha^{k+1} d(s_0,s'_0) + \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha}.
\end{aligned}

Thus the inequality holds for k+1. The bound for all k follows by induction. As k\to\infty, the first term vanishes, so all trajectories converge to a ball of radius \frac{\gamma(2\bar{d})}{1-\alpha}. ∎

