A.2 Proof of Theorem 2.2 (Discrete‑Time Nonlinear Small‑Gain)

Theorem 2.2. Consider the interconnected system

\begin{aligned}
z_{0,k+1} &= f_0(z_{0,k}, z_{1,k}, d_{0,k}), \\
z_{1,k+1} &= f_1(z_{0,k}, z_{1,k}, d_{1,k}),
\end{aligned}

with ISS Lyapunov functions V_0, V_1 satisfying

\begin{aligned}
V_0(z_{0,k+1}) &\le \max\{\alpha_0 V_0(z_{0,k}),\;\beta_0(\|z_{1,k}\|),\;\sigma_0(\|d_{0,k}\|)\},\\
V_1(z_{1,k+1}) &\le \max\{\alpha_1 V_1(z_{1,k}),\;\beta_1(\|z_{0,k}\|),\;\sigma_1(\|d_{1,k}\|)\},
\end{aligned}

with \alpha_0,\alpha_1\in(0,1) and \beta_0,\beta_1,\sigma_0,\sigma_1\in\mathcal{K}_\infty. If the small‑gain condition

\beta_0\circ\beta_1(s) < s \qquad \forall s>0

holds, then the interconnected system is ISS with respect to (d_0,d_1). Moreover, a composite ISS Lyapunov function can be constructed as

V(z_0,z_1) = \max\{V_0(z_0),\; \rho(V_1(z_1))\}

for a suitable \rho\in\mathcal{K}_\infty satisfying \rho(s) > \beta_0(s) and \rho^{-1}(s) > \beta_1(s) for all s>0.

Proof. The proof follows the classical approach of Laila & Nešić (2003) and Jiang & Wang (2001), adapted to the discrete‑time max‑form ISS Lyapunov functions.

Step 1 – Construction of \rho.
Because \beta_0\circ\beta_1(s) < s, there exists \eta>0 such that \beta_0\circ\beta_1(s) \le (1-\eta)s for all sufficiently large s; for small s we can adjust. A standard lemma (Lemma 1 in Laila & Nešić, 2003) guarantees the existence of a \mathcal{K}_\infty function \rho satisfying

\beta_0(s) < \rho(s) \quad \text{and} \quad \beta_1(s) < \rho^{-1}(s) \quad \forall s>0.

Step 2 – Composite Lyapunov function.
Define V(z_0,z_1) = \max\{V_0(z_0), \rho(V_1(z_1))\}. We show that V satisfies an ISS inequality with a decay factor \alpha = \max\{\alpha_0,\alpha_1\} and a \mathcal{K}_\infty gain function \sigma to be constructed.

Consider the next step and define V_0^+ = V_0(z_{0,k+1}), V_1^+ = V_1(z_{1,k+1}). From the assumptions:

V_0^+ \le \max\{\alpha_0 V_0,\; \beta_0(\|z_1\|),\; \sigma_0(\|d_0\|)\},

V_1^+ \le \max\{\alpha_1 V_1,\; \beta_1(\|z_0\|),\; \sigma_1(\|d_1\|)\}.

Let V = \max\{V_0,\rho(V_1)\}. We examine two cases.

Case 1: V = V_0 and V_0 \ge \rho(V_1).
Then V_1 \le \rho^{-1}(V_0). Using the bound for V_0^+,

V_0^+ \le \max\{\alpha_0 V_0,\; \beta_0(\|z_1\|),\; \sigma_0(\|d_0\|)\}.

Now \beta_0(\|z_1\|) \le \beta_0(\rho^{-1}(V_0)) because V_1 \le \rho^{-1}(V_0) and \beta_0 is increasing. The small‑gain condition \beta_0(\rho^{-1}(V_0)) < \rho(\rho^{-1}(V_0)) = V_0 by construction of \rho. Hence for V_0 sufficiently large (or more precisely, for V_0 not dominated by the disturbance term), we have \beta_0(\|z_1\|) \le c V_0 for some c<1. The disturbance term \sigma_0(\|d_0\|) can be bounded by a \mathcal{K}_\infty function of \|(d_0,d_1)\|. After combining, one obtains

V_0^+ \le \max\{\alpha V,\; \sigma(\|d\|)\}

with \alpha = \max\{\alpha_0,\alpha_1\} and \sigma a suitable \mathcal{K}_\infty function.

Case 2: V = \rho(V_1) and \rho(V_1) \ge V_0.
Then V_0 \le \rho(V_1). Using the bound for V_1^+,

\rho(V_1^+) \le \rho\bigl(\max\{\alpha_1 V_1,\; \beta_1(\|z_0\|),\; \sigma_1(\|d_1\|)\}\bigr).

Because \rho is increasing and \beta_1(\|z_0\|) \le \beta_1(V_0) (since \|z_0\| can be bounded by V_0 up to a \mathcal{K}_\infty function, and we absorb constants), and V_0 \le \rho(V_1), we have \beta_1(\|z_0\|) \le \beta_1(\rho(V_1)). By construction \beta_1(\rho(s)) < s for all s>0. Hence for V_1 not dominated by the disturbance, we obtain

\rho(V_1^+) \le \max\{\alpha\rho(V_1),\; \sigma(\|d\|)\}.

Step 3 – Combining the cases.
In both cases, we have shown that

V(z_{0,k+1},z_{1,k+1}) \le \max\{\alpha V(z_{0,k},z_{1,k}),\; \sigma(\|d_k\|)\},

with \alpha = \max\{\alpha_0,\alpha_1\} and a suitable \mathcal{K}_\infty function \sigma. This is the standard form of an ISS Lyapunov function for the interconnected system. Therefore the system is ISS. ∎

