A.3 Proof of Proposition 2.2 (Symplecticity of Symplectic Euler)

Proposition 2.2. The symplectic Euler update

p_{k+1} = p_k - \Delta t \frac{\partial H}{\partial q}(q_k, p_{k+1}), \qquad
q_{k+1} = q_k + \Delta t \frac{\partial H}{\partial p}(q_k, p_{k+1})

is a symplectic map, i.e., it preserves the canonical symplectic form \omega = dq \wedge dp.

Proof. Let z = (q,p). The map \Phi: z_k \mapsto z_{k+1} is defined implicitly by the equations above. We compute its Jacobian matrix.

Let n be the dimension of q (and p). Define the matrices

A = I + \Delta t \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial p \partial q}(q_k, p_{k+1}), \quad
B = \Delta t \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial p^2}(q_k, p_{k+1}),

C = -\Delta t \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial q^2}(q_k, p_{k+1}), \quad
D = I - \Delta t \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial p \partial q}(q_k, p_{k+1}).

The Jacobian D\Phi (with respect to z_k) is

D\Phi = \begin{pmatrix} A & B \\ C & D \end{pmatrix}.

Now the symplectic matrix is J = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & I \\ -I & 0 \end{pmatrix}. We verify that D\Phi^\top J D\Phi = J.

Compute

D\Phi^\top J D\Phi = \begin{pmatrix} A^\top & C^\top \\ B^\top & D^\top \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} 0 & I \\ -I & 0 \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} A & B \\ C & D \end{pmatrix}.

First, \begin{pmatrix} 0 & I \\ -I & 0 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} A & B \\ C & D \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} C & D \\ -A & -B \end{pmatrix}. Then

D\Phi^\top J D\Phi = \begin{pmatrix} A^\top & C^\top \\ B^\top & D^\top \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix} C & D \\ -A & -B \end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix} A^\top C - C^\top A & A^\top D - C^\top B \\ B^\top C - D^\top A & B^\top D - D^\top B \end{pmatrix}.

Because A, B, C, D are derived from the Hessian of H, they satisfy A = I + \Delta t H_{pq}, B = \Delta t H_{pp}, C = -\Delta t H_{qq}, D = I - \Delta t H_{pq} (all evaluated at the same point). Using symmetry of the Hessian (H_{pq}^\top = H_{qp}, etc.), a direct calculation shows:

· A^\top C - C^\top A = 0,
· A^\top D - C^\top B = I,
· B^\top C - D^\top A = -I,
· B^\top D - D^\top B = 0.

Hence D\Phi^\top J D\Phi = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & I \\ -I & 0 \end{pmatrix} = J. Thus \Phi is symplectic. ∎

