A.4 Proof of Theorem 2.3 (SOS Contraction)

Theorem 2.3. Suppose there exists a polynomial matrix M(s) \succ 0 and a constant \alpha \in (0,1) such that

M(s) - \alpha^2 \left(\frac{\partial \Phi}{\partial s}\right)^\top M(\Phi(s)) \frac{\partial \Phi}{\partial s} \succeq 0 \quad \text{for all } s \in \mathcal{S},

and the left‑hand side is a sum‑of‑squares polynomial matrix. Then \Phi is contracting over \mathcal{S} with rate \alpha.

Proof. The condition M(s) \succ 0 defines a Riemannian metric g_s(v,w) = v^\top M(s) w. For any virtual displacement \delta s_k (a tangent vector at s_k), the contraction LMI guarantees

\delta s_{k+1}^\top M(s_{k+1}) \delta s_{k+1} \le \alpha^2 \delta s_k^\top M(s_k) \delta s_k,

where \delta s_{k+1} = \frac{\partial \Phi}{\partial s}(s_k) \delta s_k. This inequality implies that the length of the displacement is multiplied by at most \alpha in the metric M. Therefore the Riemannian distance satisfies

d(s_{k+1}, s'_{k+1}) \le \alpha \, d(s_k, s'_k)

for all s_k, s'_k in the region where the inequality holds. The sum‑of‑squares condition is a sufficient condition for the polynomial inequality to hold for all s in the semi‑algebraic set \mathcal{S} (defined by polynomial constraints). Hence the contraction inequality holds pointwise. ∎

