A.5 Proof of Theorem 3.1 (Architectural Stability)

Theorem 3.1. If every component satisfies the local contraction condition with rate \alpha_i and ISS gain \gamma_i, and the inter‑layer coupling satisfies the nonlinear small‑gain condition, then the global software update map \Phi_{\text{sys}} is ISS with respect to disturbances, and all trajectories converge exponentially to a bounded region.

Proof. The layered architecture forms a hierarchical interconnection. For each layer \ell, let V_\ell be an ISS Lyapunov function satisfying

V_\ell(s_{\ell,k+1}) \le \max\{\alpha_\ell V_\ell(s_{\ell,k}),\; \beta_\ell(\|s_{\text{in},\ell,k}\|),\; \sigma_\ell(\|d_{\ell,k}\|)\},

where s_{\text{in},\ell} denotes the inputs from other layers. The gains \beta_\ell are derived from the contraction metrics and the coupling functions. By assumption, the coupling gains satisfy the small‑gain condition around every cycle. In particular, for the hierarchical cascade (perception → fusion → cognition → task → manipulation), the condition reduces to a product condition. Applying Theorem 2.2 recursively from the top layer downward, we construct a composite ISS Lyapunov function V = \max\{V_1, \rho_2(V_2), \dots\} that satisfies

V(s_{k+1}) \le \max\{\alpha_{\max} V(s_k),\; \sigma(\|d_k\|)\},

with \alpha_{\max} = \max_i \alpha_i and \sigma a \mathcal{K}_\infty function. Therefore \Phi_{\text{sys}} is ISS, and Theorem 2.1 yields exponential convergence to a ball. ∎

