A.6 Proof of Lemma 4.1 and Corollary 4.1 (Bounded Energy and Stability of the Mediator)

Lemma 4.1. Assume the Hamiltonian H(q,p) = \sum_i \bigl(\frac{1}{2}\|p_i\|^2 + U_i(q_i)\bigr) + \gamma \sum_{i<j} \Phi_{ij}(q_i,q_j) satisfies:

· Each U_i has bounded gradient: \|\nabla U_i(q)\| \le L_U for all q in the domain.
· Each coupling potential \Phi_{ij} has bounded gradient: \|\nabla_{q_i}\Phi_{ij}(q_i,q_j)\| \le L_\Phi for all q_i,q_j in the domain.

Then for the symplectic Euler mediator step, the momentum increment satisfies

\|p_{k+1,i} - p_{k,i}\| \le \Delta t \bigl( L_U + \gamma (n-1) L_\Phi \bigr) \quad \forall i,

where n is the number of modules.

Proof. From the mediator update:

p_{k+1,i} = p_{k,i} - \Delta t \frac{\partial H}{\partial q_i}(q_k, p_{k+1}).

The gradient of H with respect to q_i is

\frac{\partial H}{\partial q_i} = \nabla U_i(q_i) + \gamma \sum_{j\neq i} \nabla_{q_i} \Phi_{ij}(q_i,q_j).

Taking norms and using the bounded gradient assumptions:

\|p_{k+1,i} - p_{k,i}\| \le \Delta t \left( \|\nabla U_i(q_i)\| + \gamma \sum_{j\neq i} \|\nabla_{q_i}\Phi_{ij}(q_i,q_j)\| \right)
\le \Delta t \bigl( L_U + \gamma (n-1) L_\Phi \bigr).

∎

Corollary 4.1. If each module’s local dynamics are contracting with rate \alpha_i and the coupling satisfies the small‑gain condition, the system composed of the symplectic mediator and the module updates is globally ISS.

Proof. Consider one full iteration: first the mediator step (which updates the momenta p_i), then each module performs its own contraction update (which may depend on the new momentum as an input). From Lemma 4.1, the mediator step changes each module’s state by at most \Delta t (L_U + \gamma (n-1) L_\Phi). This change can be interpreted as a bounded disturbance w_k with \|w_k\| \le C\Delta t.

Each module’s contraction dynamics satisfy an ISS inequality:

d(s_{i,k+1}, s'_{i,k+1}) \le \alpha_i d(s_{i,k}, s'_{i,k}) + \gamma_i(\|w_k\|).

Thus the overall system can be viewed as a feedback interconnection where the mediator contributes a bounded disturbance to each module. The small‑gain condition (Theorem 2.2) ensures that the interconnection of these disturbed contractive systems is ISS. Therefore the composite system is ISS. ∎

