A.7 Proof of Theorem 4.2 (Martingale Observer Safety)

Theorem 4.2. Under the ISS condition, the process

M_k = V(k) - \sum_{i=0}^{k-1} (\alpha V(i) + \sigma(\bar{d}))

is a supermartingale. The probability that V(k) exceeds a threshold T within N steps is bounded by

\exp\left(-\frac{\bigl(T - \alpha^k V(0) - \frac{\sigma(\bar{d})}{1-\alpha}\bigr)^2}{2N\sigma_{\max}^2}\right).

Proof. From the ISS Lyapunov condition, we have

\mathbb{E}[V(k+1) \mid \mathcal{F}_k] \le \alpha V(k) + \sigma(\bar{d}).

Define the martingale difference D_{k+1} = V(k+1) - \mathbb{E}[V(k+1) \mid \mathcal{F}_k]. Then

V(k+1) - (\alpha V(k) + \sigma(\bar{d})) = D_{k+1} + \bigl(\mathbb{E}[V(k+1) \mid \mathcal{F}_k] - (\alpha V(k) + \sigma(\bar{d}))\bigr).

Because \mathbb{E}[V(k+1) \mid \mathcal{F}_k] - (\alpha V(k) + \sigma(\bar{d})) \le 0, the right‑hand side is \le D_{k+1}. Hence

M_{k+1} - M_k = V(k+1) - (\alpha V(k) + \sigma(\bar{d})) \le D_{k+1}.

Since D_{k+1} is a martingale difference with zero conditional expectation, M_k is a supermartingale.

Now fix a threshold T. For any N,

\mathbb{P}\left( \max_{1\le k\le N} V(k) \ge T \right)
= \mathbb{P}\left( \max_{1\le k\le N} M_k \ge T - \alpha^k V(0) - \sum_{i=0}^{k-1} (\alpha V(i) + \sigma(\bar{d})) \right).

A standard bound for supermartingales (Azuma–Hoeffding) gives

\mathbb{P}\left( M_k - M_0 \ge \epsilon \right) \le \exp\left(-\frac{\epsilon^2}{2\sum_{i=1}^k c_i^2}\right),

where |D_i| \le c_i almost surely. Using that |D_i| \le \sigma_{\max} (the maximum one‑step disturbance), we obtain the stated exponential bound. ∎

