Appendix B: Hybrid Systems Formulation

This appendix provides a rigorous treatment of the information state as a hybrid system, which is the foundation for the mapping from software states to the metric space \mathcal{S} used throughout the dissertation.

B.1 Hybrid Automaton Model

We model a software component as a hybrid automaton (Liberzon, 2003). A hybrid automaton is a tuple

\mathcal{H} = (Q, X, \text{Init}, f, \text{Guard}, \text{Reset}, \text{Inv}),

where:

· Q is a finite set of discrete modes (control flow states).
· X \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n is the continuous state space.
· \text{Init} \subseteq Q \times X is the set of initial states.
· For each mode q \in Q, f_q: X \to \mathbb{R}^n is a Lipschitz continuous vector field describing the continuous evolution (discrete‑time: x_{k+1} = f_q(x_k)).
· \text{Guard}: Q \times Q \to 2^{X} assigns a guard set for each transition from q to q'.
· \text{Reset}: Q \times Q \times X \to X assigns a reset map for each transition.
· \text{Inv}: Q \to 2^{X} is an invariant set that must hold while in mode q.

In the discrete‑time setting, the system executes as follows: at each step, given current mode q and continuous state x, the system either:

1. Stays in mode q and updates x to f_q(x), provided the new state satisfies \text{Inv}(q); or
2. Transitions to a mode q' if x \in \text{Guard}(q,q'), and then updates x to \text{Reset}(q,q',x) (which may be the identity).

B.2 Information State Mapping

For a hybrid automaton \mathcal{H}, we define the information state as

\mathcal{I}(q,x) = (v_q, x) \in \mathbb{R}^{m+n},

where v_q is a fixed vector in \mathbb{R}^m assigned to mode q. We require the vectors v_q to be separated: there exists \delta > 0 such that \|v_q - v_{q'}\| \ge \delta for all distinct q,q'. The continuous part x is unchanged.

The dynamics on the information state are induced by the hybrid automaton. When the system stays in a mode, the continuous update is x_{k+1} = f_q(x_k) and v_q remains constant. When a transition occurs, the mode changes to q' and the continuous state is reset (possibly). The mapping \mathcal{I} is Lipschitz on the product metric because the discrete part has a fixed separation and the continuous part is Lipschitz.

B.3 Assumption: Dwell‑Time

To ensure stability across mode switches, we impose a dwell‑time condition:

Assumption B.1 (Dwell‑Time). There exists \tau_d > 0 such that any mode of the system is active for at least \tau_d time steps before a transition occurs. In discrete time, this means the number of consecutive steps in any mode is at least \tau_d.

This assumption prevents Zeno behavior and allows us to treat each mode as an independent system with a common Lyapunov function or to use multiple Lyapunov functions with a sufficiently slow switching rate.

B.4 ISS for Hybrid Systems

Under the dwell‑time assumption, a hybrid system is ISS if each mode’s continuous dynamics is ISS (with a common Lyapunov function or with matching gains) and the switches do not cause instability. A sufficient condition is the existence of a common ISS Lyapunov function V that satisfies

V(f_q(x)) \le \lambda V(x) + \sigma(\|d\|)

for all modes q, and such that V does not increase at resets. If such a function exists, the hybrid system is ISS.

In the OSSA framework, we assume that each component is implemented in a way that guarantees a common ISS Lyapunov function (e.g., by using the same contraction metric across modes or by verifying that the resets are contractive). This is consistent with the LipSwish decorator and the SOS verification applied to each mode individually, and then combined via the small‑gain theorem.

