Appendix E: Related Work

A detailed survey of formal methods, control‑theoretic software engineering, and architectural patterns in robotics.

E.1 Contraction Analysis and Stability of Software

Contraction analysis was introduced by Lohmiller & Slotine (1998) as a tool for analyzing nonlinear system stability. The discrete‑time extension and its application to learning systems was developed by Tsukamoto, Chung & Slotine (2021). The idea of using contraction to guarantee the stability of software systems has been explored in the context of contract‑based design (Sangiovanni‑Vincentelli et al., 2012) and control‑theoretic software adaptation (Klein et al., 2009). However, these works typically treat the software as a plant to be controlled, rather than embedding the contraction property into the architectural patterns themselves.

E.2 Input‑to‑State Stability (ISS) and Small‑Gain

The ISS framework for nonlinear systems was introduced by Sontag (1989). The small‑gain theorem for interconnected ISS systems in continuous time was proven by Jiang & Wang (2001). The discrete‑time version used in this dissertation follows the work of Laila & Nešić (2003), who provided a Lyapunov‑based formulation for discrete‑time ISS and small‑gain. These results have been applied to networked control systems (Nešić & Teel, 2004) and robotic systems (Bullo et al., 2025). Our contribution is to cast the small‑gain condition as an architectural constraint, enforced through a mediator pattern.

E.3 Symplectic Integration and Geometric Mechanics

Symplectic integrators preserve the geometric structure of Hamiltonian systems (Hairer, Lubich & Wanner, 2006). The use of symplectic methods in robotics is common for simulating mechanical systems (e.g., the variational integrator approach of Marsden & West, 2001). The novel aspect of this dissertation is the use of a symplectic mediator to structure communication between cognitive modules, ensuring that the coupling does not introduce artificial energy.

E.4 Sum‑of‑Squares Programming for Lyapunov Functions

Sum‑of‑squares programming (Parrilo, 2000) provides a computational approach to verify polynomial Lyapunov functions. It has been applied to contraction analysis (Manchester & Slotine, 2017) and to neural network verification (Raghunathan et al., 2018). The OSSA framework extends this by using SOS certificates as compile‑time guarantees for software components.

E.5 Hybrid Systems and Switched Systems

The theory of hybrid systems (Liberzon, 2003) provides tools for analyzing systems with both continuous and discrete dynamics. The dwell‑time condition is a standard way to ensure stability of switched systems. Our use of a hybrid automaton to model software modes is a natural fit for the OSSA framework.

